: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-9-sewing-a-mock-up-after-a-new-pattern/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-9-sewing-a-mock-up-after-a-new-pattern/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2017-11-30T17:05:08+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2017-11-30T17:05:08+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2017"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 9. Sewing a Mock-up after a New Pattern."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 9. Sewing a Mock-up after a New Pattern."><meta itemprop="description" content="In this tutorial, we will talk about sewing mock-up corsets. I will use mock-up corsets to demonstrate you various styles, point out common errors"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding and Evening Dresses. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding and evening dresses. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 9. Sewing a Mock-up after a New Pattern.</h1><p><strong>In this tutorial, we will talk about sewing mock-up corsets. </strong>I will use mock-up corsets to demonstrate you various styles, point out common errors, and explain possible ways of fixing them.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%209.files/image003.jpg" alt="gold2tskr-078 v:shapes="></p><p>For many years I have been highlighting that each new course dedicated to a corset garment comes together with a new pattern which you need to get acquainted with!</p><p><strong>And the best way to get acquainted with a new pattern is to sew a mock-up garment after it. </strong></p><p>To be honest, I am a little surprised at some frequently asked questions from your E-mails: “Do I have to sew a mock-up? Why should I have to do it when I can just sew a corset using your patterns?”</p><p>Believe me, I do not insist on your sewing mock-ups − the choice is yours! But if you want to get good results, if you want to sew a great garment for your client from the first try, then you should understand the pattern very well before cutting high-quality expensive fabric and sewing with it.</p><p><strong>Let me give you several points in favour of sewing mock-ups. </strong></p><p><strong>I will start from the simplest cases: </strong></p><p>- The pattern was printed out wrong;</p><p>- You got the joining order wrong or confused the top of some piece with its bottom.</p><p><strong>Is there any way to protect yourself from such mistakes? Only by sewing a mock-up! </strong></p><p><strong>There are even more important arguments. </strong></p><p><strong>Let me ask you a question: how to take correct and accurate measurements off a paper pattern? </strong></p><p>Of course, you can measure all key circumference lines on the pattern, sum up the values, get what will seem to be correct measurements, and rely on them when adjusting the pattern to your client’s size.</p><p>But you must know that fabric is not the same as paper! Fabric will behave in a totally different way after you make your garment.</p><p><strong>Moreover, every dressmaker has her own sewing manner and habits based on her personal experience (and many of you have a lot of such experience).</strong></p><p><strong>What am I trying to say? </strong></p><p><strong>All my patterns, for example, include 1.2cm or 0.5” seam allowances. </strong>You think you keep them at that 1.2cm when sewing a garment, but in fact you may be making them 1.1cm or 1.3cm.</p><p><strong>What will happen in this case? </strong>Of course, you will still get the right corset shape (except, maybe, bust princess seams) as long as you sew parallel to the sewing lines on the pattern. You will feel like you have done everything right, but the size of the garment will be radically different. Let me emphasize that this can happen just because my patterns were designed for a garment of a particular size with regard to my individual sewing habits. This explains why different dressmakers can end up with garments of different sizes even when they use the same pattern.</p><p><strong>Let us move ahead though. Suppose you have made a mock-up after my standard pattern and you are taking measurements off it to compare them with client’s measurements.</strong> Every seamstress has her own habits here, just like with the sewing. You measure your client the way you always do: put the measuring tape where you always put it, tighten it the way you always tighten it, etc. And, therefore, you need to know the measurements of the standard pattern taken your way, too!</p><p><strong>How can you know it unless you sew and measure a mock-up? The only way to obtain the actual measurements of your standard pattern is to measure a mock-up in your habitual manner. And then you can adjust it with respect to your client’s measurements taken the same way. </strong></p><p>I also recommend you should stuff all hollows after putting your mock-up on the dress-form before measuring it. Just use bits of padding polyester or foam to give the mock-up its proper shape, i.e. imitate a female figure. Be careful to adjust the shape of the dress-form after the mock-up, not the other way round.</p><p><strong>And you will get a dress-form customized after your client’s figure</strong> if you sew another mock-up after making all size-related pattern adjustments, put it on the dress-form very neatly, and stuff all hollows.</p><p><strong>This will make further work a lot easier!</strong></p><p>You will be able to double-check all measurements taken off your client and do fittings right on the dress-form.</p><p><strong>There are situations when sewing a mock-up is compulsory. Let me give you some examples. </strong></p><p><strong>Suppose you have a set of tutorials on sewing a wedding outfit made of a corset and a full skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>The corset pattern is included, as always. </strong>But it provides for additional volume in the stomach area required for even distribution of the top edge of the full skirt (otherwise there will be very messy folds emerging from under the bottom edge of the corset).</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%209.files/image005.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>What if your client wants a wedding outfit with just the same top (i.e. she is happy with the corset) but a narrow skirt? </strong></p><p>You will need to adjust the initial corset pattern to ensure tight enough fit in the stomach. One of the possible ways of doing it is to make straight darts going down from the waistline of the corset.</p><p>It is very hard to do without sewing a mock-up first.</p><p><strong>There are opposite cases</strong> when you have a pattern of a corset coupled with a pattern of a narrow skirt, but your client wants a full skirt.</p><p><strong>Again, you will really need a mock-up! </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%209.files/image007.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Besides, sewing a mock-up allows you to make minor adjustments to the position and direction of princess seams with respect to your client’s preferences. </strong>You can re-draw them right on the mock-up, cut it along the new lines, and get a new pattern fully corresponding with the chosen garment style.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/Tutorial%209.files/image009.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Of course, we will talk about princess seams and related adjustments in great detail a little later. </strong>I will, for example, give you reasons for the key rule from all my courses which instructs you to avoid changing the configuration of bust princess seams, especially if you are not very experienced in corset-making.</p><p>With a mock-up you can adjust the position of princess seams if you notice that it does not coincide with their desired position on the sketch.</p><p><strong>And this means only a mock-up can show whether you have chosen the right pattern for the dress you want to sew. </strong>This is something we will talk about a lot in this book.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20boat.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Boat-Neck Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker%20essential/patterns/4%20curves%20corset%20-%20strapless.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Strapless Corset with 4 Princess Seams</a><br><a href=